description:
In this episode, I am joined by Ras Mic, a full stack engineer & YouTuber, where we dive deep into the frameworks and strategies on how to best use Cursor AI. Mic shares his unique insights into how to use and set up Cursor to make the experience of building on top of Cursor as easy and seamless as possible. Learn how to use Cursor like a pro!

1) Plan before coding 
â€¢ Sketch out ideas (Figma, iPad, paper)
â€¢ Use V0 for mockups (10-15 prompts minimum)
â€¢ Set your AI assistant up for success
"Half the game is acting like a developer" - Mike

2) Use cursor.directory for better prompts 
â€¢ Copy tech-specific prompts
â€¢ Create .cursor_rules file in project root
â€¢ Drastically improves Cursor's output
Pro tip: Customize prompts for your exact tech stack

3) Tag relevant documentation 
â€¢ Add official docs to Cursor (Next.js, Supabase, etc.)
â€¢ Ensures up-to-date, accurate responses
â€¢ Cursor reads docs when answering queries

4)  Ask other AI models when stuck 
â€¢ Copy errors to Claude, GPT-4, etc.
â€¢ Include failed solutions for better context
â€¢ Different models can solve problems others can't

5)  Use AI to explain code 
â€¢ Great for learning & documentation
â€¢ Ask to explain like you're a beginner
â€¢ Follow up on confusing concepts
"The more you do this, the more you learn patterns" - Mike

6) Leverage existing code templates 
â€¢ Start with boilerplate (auth, DB, payments)
â€¢ Build on top of proven foundations
â€¢ Saves time on repetitive tasks

7) Add comments to your code 
â€¢ Ask AI to explain & document your code
â€¢ Improves readability & understanding
â€¢ Great for team collaboration

8)  Duplicate & modify existing functionality 
â€¢ Copy working code from other parts of your project
â€¢ Ask AI to adapt it for new use cases
â€¢ Provides context for better results
Key takeaway: Give AI as much context as possible for best results!

comments.text: Great video. As someone who has been learning Python with a database implementation using first VS Code/Github Copilot and now with Cursor, it was really heartening to hear an experienced programmer give voice to the frustrations that I have had about exploring how my app is going to work. Things have really taken off for me now that Iâ€™m not limited to just 10 files for context like with GitHub Copilot. One thing that Iâ€™ve found was really helpful from when I had file limitations was to create a package that queries the database and creates a file that lists all table names sowing the column names with data types, any constraints/key relationships and the top 5 rows as example data for each table. This has helped reduce the number of assumptions that the AI makes. I also have it create a file for each class showing method names inputs/outputs and a sentence description of purpose. This has helped when creating new processes since the AI usually doesnâ€™t need to see the whole code when referencing something to be included, it just needs input/output and purpose. Both of these run at the beginning of each test execution to stay up to date. Iâ€™ve also started having it capture my errors in the terminal and writing them to a an errors.md file that I include in my context. I have a Project design folder that has an AI instructions file that details how the AI should interact with me. In the instructions I tell it that each time I tell it to review the errors file it looks at errors.md and a file called implemented_actions.md to generate a file called proposed_action.md that provides details about the fixes it wants to implement based upon the error.md and what it implemented previously. After I tell it how I want to proceed it creates a new implemented_actions.md file which contains the new action as well as the previous couple iterations of implemented solutions. That way the next run it can see if it is repeatedly trying to fix the same issue. This has really improved my interactions since after a point it seems like the AI can get stupid if I go too long without resetting the session. This way if I reset the session it knows exactly where we are. If we run into an issue multiple times I tell it to update the guidelines files that are in my project details folder. And then Iâ€™ve referenced the guidelines files in the AI instructions file. A have separate guideline files for structure, db interaction, object creation, logging, unit tests, and a couple of other things. I just periodically ask it to review the guidelines files and apply any updates as appropriate. Also, I love using the word â€˜robustâ€™ when I describe an implementation for something. I get really good results with that. This will probably all turn into an agent that I run after each program code execution. Thatâ€™s what Iâ€™m exploring now.
